00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:05.630
JOHN MERRIFIELD: So tell us
over here about your new book,

00:01:05.630 --> 00:01:09.297
"The Only Pirate at the Party,"
which is a lovely title.

00:01:09.297 --> 00:01:10.580
LINDSEY STIRLING: Thank you.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:14.560
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Can you
first take us back to violin,

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:16.970
and talk to us about
how you started violin,

00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:19.852
and when you knew music is
something you wanted to do.

00:01:19.852 --> 00:01:21.560
LINDSEY STIRLING: So
I started the violin

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:24.450
when I was six years old, and
it was because my parents,

00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:26.900
they used to play classical
music on this old record

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:28.620
player in our
house all the time,

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:31.870
and they would take us to
orchestra concerts in LA

00:01:31.870 --> 00:01:33.520
at the time was where we lived.

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:35.810
And I noticed that
the violinists,

00:01:35.810 --> 00:01:38.990
they got all the
solos, they got to play

00:01:38.990 --> 00:01:40.332
the fast, interesting parts.

00:01:40.332 --> 00:01:41.790
And so I started
begging my parents

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:43.490
for lessons when I was tiny.

00:01:43.490 --> 00:01:45.550
And I started when I was six.

00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:47.280
And it was always
something I loved,

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:51.840
and something that I always
saw as a glorified hobby.

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:54.900
I went to college, actually, for
something completely different,

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:57.760
just because I always
wanted to keep it my hobby.

00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:59.290
I was always wanted
to love music.

00:01:59.290 --> 00:02:01.020
I never wanted to resent it.

00:02:01.020 --> 00:02:03.590
And then when I was sitting
in class at college,

00:02:03.590 --> 00:02:05.140
all I could think
about was music.

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:07.470
I was studying to
be a therapist,

00:02:07.470 --> 00:02:10.810
and I was spending all my
free time at open mic nights

00:02:10.810 --> 00:02:13.100
and with bands,
and I just realized

00:02:13.100 --> 00:02:15.880
I'm always going to regret this
if I don't chase after this.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:17.250
I have to give it a try.

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:19.640
And thank heavens I did.

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:21.990
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Worked
out all right, I think.

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:24.409
So you talked about your
parents briefly there.

00:02:24.409 --> 00:02:25.950
Can you tell us a
little more about--

00:02:25.950 --> 00:02:27.203
and you say this in your
book-- about your parents

00:02:27.203 --> 00:02:29.070
and the influence
they had on you

00:02:29.070 --> 00:02:31.210
younger, and that motivation?

00:02:31.210 --> 00:02:32.370
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah.

00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:36.000
My parents were
always so supportive

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.730
of me and my sisters, all
of us expressing ourselves,

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.190
and expressing our creativity.

00:02:40.190 --> 00:02:43.220
And whether it was my mom
teaching me how to sew,

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:47.950
or them encouraging me to
pursue music, or my dad,

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:52.110
he was a writer, and he would
read as bedtime stories scripts

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:54.810
that he had written when
he was trying to make it

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:56.770
in the movie business.

00:02:56.770 --> 00:03:01.710
And so I just grew up with this
idea that creativity is life,

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:04.210
and creativity is therapeutic.

00:03:04.210 --> 00:03:04.880
It's everything.

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:06.210
It's fun it's joyous.

00:03:06.210 --> 00:03:10.540
And also, I think the fact
that my dad chased his dream

00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:11.290
when he was young.

00:03:11.290 --> 00:03:13.430
And he had all these stories
about going places, and meeting

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:14.763
people, and shaking their hands.

00:03:14.763 --> 00:03:17.760
And I remember I'd tell my
dad, even when I was tiny,

00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:19.577
Dad, I want to live
a life like you.

00:03:19.577 --> 00:03:20.410
I want to go places.

00:03:20.410 --> 00:03:21.770
I want to shake people's hands.

00:03:21.770 --> 00:03:24.870
And I think I attribute a
lot of where I'm at today

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:26.760
because my dad
chased his dreams.

00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:28.970
And even though it almost
gave me more courage

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:31.220
to chase them because he
felt like he was better,

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:33.570
even though he didn't
get his, necessarily,

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:35.690
at the time he was
chasing them, he still

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:39.230
had all these amazing stories
and was better for it.

00:03:39.230 --> 00:03:42.410
And so I was like,
well, even for trying,

00:03:42.410 --> 00:03:44.842
it's OK to try and not get
exactly to where you want,

00:03:44.842 --> 00:03:46.050
because you'll get somewhere.

00:03:46.050 --> 00:03:46.520
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Yeah.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:47.937
So your family has
a writing gene.

00:03:47.937 --> 00:03:49.020
LINDSEY STIRLING: It does.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:51.480
I'm in a family of
literary writers.

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:53.400
My parents were
both English majors.

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:55.570
My sister Brooke
wrote my book with me,

00:03:55.570 --> 00:03:57.850
or was the writer of the book.

00:03:57.850 --> 00:03:59.015
And so--

00:03:59.015 --> 00:04:00.632
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:00.632 --> 00:04:02.465
JOHN MERRIFIELD: And
Brooke, give us a wave.

00:04:02.465 --> 00:04:05.596
You're going to come up here a
little later and talk further.

00:04:05.596 --> 00:04:08.036
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:09.039 --> 00:04:10.830
LINDSEY STIRLING: I
can't steal the credit,

00:04:10.830 --> 00:04:12.714
because she's in the room.

00:04:12.714 --> 00:04:14.010
Just kidding.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:17.760
JOHN MERRIFIELD: So what
are your thoughts on-- a lot

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:19.589
of YouTubers are writing books.

00:04:19.589 --> 00:04:21.290
Was that a motivation
for you as well?

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:22.520
Or what are your
thoughts on that?

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:23.800
LINDSEY STIRLING: Actually,
we started the book

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:25.383
three years ago, and
I'm sure they all

00:04:25.383 --> 00:04:27.730
started theirs years before.

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:31.050
We all probably were working on
them silently at the same time.

00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:35.300
And I think it's really awesome
that my YouTube friends,

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:38.870
they're my peers, we
all started together

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:40.690
in this weird world
of YouTube, where

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:43.920
we were the rejects of the
entertainment industry.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:47.585
We were seen as, oh,
they're YouTubers.

00:04:47.585 --> 00:04:49.170
We were the freak category.

00:04:49.170 --> 00:04:52.350
And so it's so cool to
see these people that

00:04:52.350 --> 00:04:55.040
are my friends-- we're like a
little sorority that's grown up

00:04:55.040 --> 00:04:58.760
together-- and to see
Grace get a show on TV,

00:04:58.760 --> 00:05:01.300
and then to see Miranda
on "Jimmy Fallon"

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:03.600
and a writing a
book, and everybody

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:05.820
doing these amazing
things, and winning awards.

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:08.377
It's like go team, internet.

00:05:08.377 --> 00:05:10.210
We're a family, and so
it's really exciting.

00:05:10.210 --> 00:05:11.668
And we all have
each other's books,

00:05:11.668 --> 00:05:13.810
and we send them to each.

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:14.639
It's a family.

00:05:14.639 --> 00:05:15.680
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Awesome.

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:20.430
And so within your book,
what was your main motivation

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:23.570
to start out and think, I've
had this amazing career.

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:25.860
Let's write a book, talk
a little further about it.

00:05:25.860 --> 00:05:28.540
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah, well, I
wanted it to be several things.

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:31.360
I wanted people to read it,
and laugh, and enjoy it,

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:34.840
and be filled with positivity.

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:37.385
But at the same time, I think
one of the big motivations

00:05:37.385 --> 00:05:40.210
to write the book was I felt
like I had some experiences

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:43.790
and stories that I wanted to
share, because here at meet

00:05:43.790 --> 00:05:47.070
and greets and at shows,
people will ask me questions.

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:49.970
And it's a very quick
process at a meet and greet.

00:05:49.970 --> 00:05:52.460
You don't get to spend an
hour chatting with someone.

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:57.010
And girls would whisper to
me, I struggle with anorexia.

00:05:57.010 --> 00:05:58.140
How did you get through it?

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:00.640
And what do you say to
someone in that moment?

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:03.110
And so it just made me
think over and over again,

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:05.660
gosh, when I was going through
depression and anorexia,

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:07.720
I felt so isolated and so alone.

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:09.710
And people are
very afraid to talk

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:11.150
about those kind of things.

00:06:11.150 --> 00:06:13.260
And it took me a
really long time

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:15.500
to even realize I had a
problem, because I thought,

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:18.240
no, depression I
don't have that.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:19.140
That's not me.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:21.140
But the thing is, I think
that this is something

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:23.420
that a lot of people,
unknowingly or knowingly,

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:24.180
go through.

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:26.420
And so I wanted to
bring awareness to it,

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:29.472
and also provide,
hopefully, hope for someone.

00:06:29.472 --> 00:06:31.180
Like when I felt
hopeless, hopefully they

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:34.160
can find hope, and realize
that they can get through it,

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:37.640
and they can be who
they want to be.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:40.829
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Now, you have
a chapter called "Life with Ed."

00:06:40.829 --> 00:06:42.370
Do you mind talking
a little bit more

00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:45.147
about the title of that
and that experience?

00:06:45.147 --> 00:06:46.230
LINDSEY STIRLING: Totally.

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:49.460
So "Life without
Ed" is a book that I

00:06:49.460 --> 00:06:51.810
read when I was
struggling with anorexia,

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:55.220
and it was probably one of the
most helpful books that I read.

00:06:55.220 --> 00:06:58.810
I read a lot about anorexia
when I realized I had a problem.

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:02.190
And it was a book where it
separated the eating disorder

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:02.820
and this girl.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:06.580
Her therapist had taught her
to call her eating disorder Ed.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:09.850
And so for the first time
I realized, oh my gosh,

00:07:09.850 --> 00:07:11.700
my eating disorder isn't me.

00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:13.350
It's not my brain.

00:07:13.350 --> 00:07:15.670
This is something
that has come into me,

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:17.260
and it's something
that I can get out.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:19.664
It's a separate part of my
brain that I can say, go away.

00:07:19.664 --> 00:07:21.955
And in and this book, she
talks to her eating disorder,

00:07:21.955 --> 00:07:24.020
and she calls it, and
she personifies it.

00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:26.430
And so these voices that
would come into her head

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:28.263
telling her negative
things, and telling her

00:07:28.263 --> 00:07:30.790
that she was
worthless, or whatever,

00:07:30.790 --> 00:07:32.446
she would talk
back to this voice

00:07:32.446 --> 00:07:33.820
with the other
side of her brain,

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:36.430
and say, no, I'm not worthless.

00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:38.100
And she would have
these conversations.

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:40.610
And as much as it sounds
schizophrenic and multiple

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:42.600
personality
disorder, I did this.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:46.470
And it allowed me to feel
like I had the ability

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:48.210
to take control
over my brain again

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:50.740
and kick out this very
unhealthy part of myself.

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:52.250
And you know, it's still there.

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:54.640
It's still a little part of
me that will always be there,

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:57.330
but I know how to
talk to it now.

00:07:57.330 --> 00:07:59.340
And it actually hides
most of the time.

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:00.710
It's usually not there.

00:08:00.710 --> 00:08:03.870
And when I first learned
about an eating disorder,

00:08:03.870 --> 00:08:05.480
and I first started
researching it,

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:09.410
I was so upset, because I read
that it's an incurable disease.

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:10.970
And I was like,
who wants to hear

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:13.700
that the worst part of
yourself is incurable

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:15.300
and you're always
going to have it?

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:18.540
And now I understand why they
say that, but at the same time,

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:20.120
it's not a part of
my everyday life.

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:21.720
It's not a part
of my weekly life.

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:24.120
When I get really stressed
out, Ed starts to come back,

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.760
and I know how to talk to
it and tell it to go away.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:28.950
And so that's why I
wanted that chapter

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:32.500
to be in there, because I wanted
to express that it is curable.

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:33.530
You can get rid of it.

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:34.870
You can take things
out of your life,

00:08:34.870 --> 00:08:36.539
and you can determine
who you want to be,

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:38.830
and you don't have to let
the hard things we go through

00:08:38.830 --> 00:08:39.743
determine who we are.

00:08:39.743 --> 00:08:40.659
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Yeah.

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:41.169
That's awesome.

00:08:41.169 --> 00:08:41.730
Thank you.

00:08:41.730 --> 00:08:43.710
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:50.070
So in that same experience,
opening up about that,

00:08:50.070 --> 00:08:52.980
you're a great role
model for other people.

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:55.810
Do you mind talking a little
bit about your core principles

00:08:55.810 --> 00:08:57.500
and that influence on your life?

00:08:57.500 --> 00:09:00.820
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah, you
know, a lot of people ask me,

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:03.670
oh, how do you try
to stay grounded?

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:06.260
My life has literally
flipped upside down

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:07.990
in the last four years.

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:09.830
I'm in a completely
different place

00:09:09.830 --> 00:09:12.190
than I ever thought
I would ever be in,

00:09:12.190 --> 00:09:16.110
and everything from my personal
life to my professional life

00:09:16.110 --> 00:09:17.770
has just changed.

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:20.980
And the one thing, I think,
that's kept me very consistent

00:09:20.980 --> 00:09:21.950
is two things.

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:27.050
It's my family and my spiritual
beliefs, my religious beliefs.

00:09:27.050 --> 00:09:31.550
I was raised in a very,
very religious family.

00:09:31.550 --> 00:09:35.030
We went to church every week,
and we had specific principles

00:09:35.030 --> 00:09:35.720
and guidelines.

00:09:35.720 --> 00:09:39.270
And I decided when I started
to see my career taking off,

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:40.640
it scared me.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:43.840
And I thought, what if I change?

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:45.430
I like the person that I am.

00:09:45.430 --> 00:09:48.050
I like Lindsey, the
core of the person

00:09:48.050 --> 00:09:50.250
that my parents raised me to be.

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:52.655
And I don't want to
become something I'm not.

00:09:52.655 --> 00:09:54.780
I don't want to become a
scary-- you hear about how

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:56.684
people change, and you
know, Justin Bieber

00:09:56.684 --> 00:09:57.600
fell off the deep end.

00:09:57.600 --> 00:10:00.420
You're like, ahh, what do I do?

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:02.480
And so I made a decision.

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:04.890
And it was almost like
a promise to me and God.

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:06.687
And some people
call it-- I think

00:10:06.687 --> 00:10:09.020
most people that are artistic
have a belief in something

00:10:09.020 --> 00:10:10.060
greater than themselves.

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:10.910
And to me, it's God.

00:10:10.910 --> 00:10:13.310
And I made a promise
to God that I

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:15.120
would stay true
to the principles

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:17.820
that I had right then,
my standards of dress,

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:21.545
my standards of lifestyle,
and my spirituality.

00:10:21.545 --> 00:10:24.170
And as long as I've kept
that in the forefront

00:10:24.170 --> 00:10:27.180
of my life and a foundation,
as much as everything else has

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:30.000
changed, my religious
beliefs and my family

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.650
have kept me feeling like
I'm the same Lindsey that I

00:10:33.650 --> 00:10:36.860
have grown up to be,
and that I want to stay.

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:39.840
And I plan to keep that as
a foundation of my life.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:41.704
And I think it's kept me sane.

00:10:41.704 --> 00:10:42.620
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Yeah.

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:44.650
There's a funny
chapter in your book.

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:47.200
This is the only spoiler I give.

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:49.150
But it's where you say
the chapter on drugs,

00:10:49.150 --> 00:10:50.810
and rock 'n' roll,
and everything,

00:10:50.810 --> 00:10:52.310
and then it's one
sentence, and it's

00:10:52.310 --> 00:10:54.550
like, I didn't do any
of that, so moving on.

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:55.550
LINDSEY STIRLING: Right.

00:10:55.550 --> 00:10:57.390
JOHN MERRIFIELD: And
that was a good chapter.

00:10:57.390 --> 00:10:57.660
LINDSEY STIRLING: Thank you.

00:10:57.660 --> 00:10:58.180
Thank you.

00:10:58.180 --> 00:11:00.554
It was the easiest in the
audio book, when I got to that.

00:11:00.554 --> 00:11:01.780
It was like, chapter down.

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:02.955
Yes.

00:11:02.955 --> 00:11:04.330
JOHN MERRIFIELD:
Now, do you mind

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:06.810
talking a little bit about
the chapter "No Man's Land"?

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:09.192
I think it starts leading up
to the title and everything.

00:11:09.192 --> 00:11:10.150
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah.

00:11:10.150 --> 00:11:11.840
You know, there
was another theme

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:13.820
that I wanted to
bring up in the book,

00:11:13.820 --> 00:11:15.760
that it's OK to be different.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:18.860
And one of the first
chapters in the book

00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:20.720
says that sometimes
being different

00:11:20.720 --> 00:11:22.890
feels a lot like being alone.

00:11:22.890 --> 00:11:25.562
And it's not like I've gone
through my life being like,

00:11:25.562 --> 00:11:27.770
I want to look different,
and I want to be different,

00:11:27.770 --> 00:11:30.460
and I want to be quirky and
weird and have stand out.

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:34.940
A lot of times, I just feel
like every single person

00:11:34.940 --> 00:11:37.960
is different when we're true
to our authentic selves,

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:39.830
and that's OK.

00:11:39.830 --> 00:11:43.300
It's Acceptance is very
different from fitting in.

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:45.300
Fitting in is changing
yourself to fit with what

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:46.670
someone else wants you to be.

00:11:46.670 --> 00:11:49.014
And acceptance is being
accepted by those you

00:11:49.014 --> 00:11:50.180
love for who you really are.

00:11:50.180 --> 00:11:52.500
And so "No Man's
Land" was a chapter

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:54.170
I talked about how
sometimes I feel

00:11:54.170 --> 00:11:56.840
like I'm in the middle of
two very different worlds.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:59.470
There's my religious
side and the side where

00:11:59.470 --> 00:12:02.270
I like to be frugal,
and I drive the same car

00:12:02.270 --> 00:12:03.370
I drove in high school.

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:05.560
And there's that side of myself.

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:06.530
And then there's this--

00:12:06.530 --> 00:12:07.585
JOHN MERRIFIELD: You
really drive the same car

00:12:07.585 --> 00:12:07.880
since high school.

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:09.360
LINDSEY STIRLING: Well,
actually in the book I do.

00:12:09.360 --> 00:12:10.880
My car died a couple months ago.

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:11.880
JOHN MERRIFIELD: I know.

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:13.024
I thought it had died.

00:12:13.024 --> 00:12:14.940
LINDSEY STIRLING: And I
was very sad about it.

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:16.621
It died on the 405,
and I just sat there

00:12:16.621 --> 00:12:17.620
on the side of the road.

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:19.328
It was the third time
it died in a month,

00:12:19.328 --> 00:12:20.880
and I was like, we're done.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:21.560
JOHN MERRIFIELD: We're done.

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:22.768
LINDSEY STIRLING: We're done.

00:12:22.768 --> 00:12:26.440
But when the book was completed,
I had the same-- so it's a lie.

00:12:29.494 --> 00:12:31.160
So there's that side
of myself, and then

00:12:31.160 --> 00:12:34.160
there's the side of myself
that I'm in the music industry,

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:37.510
and a lot of that
industry sometimes

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:39.550
falls in the sex, drugs,
and rock 'n' roll.

00:12:39.550 --> 00:12:41.760
Not everybody, but
that's the stigma

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:44.910
of a lot of what you
come into contact with,

00:12:44.910 --> 00:12:47.290
and I feel sometimes
like I toe the line

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:48.610
of two very different worlds.

00:12:48.610 --> 00:12:51.110
And I'm in the middle, and
either side a lot of times

00:12:51.110 --> 00:12:53.337
can't understand the other.

00:12:53.337 --> 00:12:54.920
But at the end of
the chapter, it also

00:12:54.920 --> 00:12:58.520
talks about how it's OK.

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:00.750
My tour manager writes me
this letter that I realize,

00:13:00.750 --> 00:13:03.260
yes, sometimes maybe I do feel
like I'm in no man's land,

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:05.100
but there are people
that understand me,

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:07.100
and there are people that
I've surrounded myself

00:13:07.100 --> 00:13:10.944
with that get it, and love
that about me, and respect it.

00:13:10.944 --> 00:13:12.860
And so I've just learned,
over and over again,

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:16.370
even in these times when I'm
like, oh I feel like I'm alone,

00:13:16.370 --> 00:13:18.740
there are always people that
that's why they love you,

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:20.570
is for the things that
make you different.

00:13:20.570 --> 00:13:23.054
And no one's really
in no man's land.

00:13:23.054 --> 00:13:24.500
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Wow.

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:28.140
So YouTube being your main
platform, you write about this,

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:30.000
but it's a very public
platform, right?

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.708
That you can comment,
people can comment.

00:13:31.708 --> 00:13:32.904
You can see that.

00:13:32.904 --> 00:13:34.570
Tell us about how
when you first started

00:13:34.570 --> 00:13:36.305
getting really big
on YouTube, how

00:13:36.305 --> 00:13:38.630
you dealt with maybe the
comments, the good, the bad,

00:13:38.630 --> 00:13:40.070
And how you went through that.

00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:41.476
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yes.

00:13:41.476 --> 00:13:42.600
You know, it's interesting.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:45.970
I have some friends that are
YouTubers that say, oh, you

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:48.140
get used to the comments.

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:52.350
You just ignore them, and it
doesn't matter at some point.

00:13:52.350 --> 00:13:55.241
Maybe I'm different, but I
feel like the hurtful comments,

00:13:55.241 --> 00:13:56.990
they're always going
to hurt a little bit,

00:13:56.990 --> 00:13:58.849
especially when they
you in that spot

00:13:58.849 --> 00:14:00.640
that you're sensitive
to, that you're like,

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:03.225
oh, I was hoping nobody
would comment on that.

00:14:03.225 --> 00:14:04.830
Everybody has their
little things.

00:14:04.830 --> 00:14:06.830
I don't know if any of
you watch "The Bachelor,"

00:14:06.830 --> 00:14:09.160
but the gal was
talking about her toes.

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:09.930
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Yeah,
she started crying, right?

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:11.030
LINDSEY STIRLING: She's
starts crying about her toes.

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:13.155
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Not that
I watch it, but my wife--

00:14:13.155 --> 00:14:14.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:14.740
LINDSEY STIRLING: Caught ya!

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:15.510
Your wife, right?

00:14:15.510 --> 00:14:16.607
Your wife.

00:14:16.607 --> 00:14:18.190
Anyways, I thought
that was hilarious,

00:14:18.190 --> 00:14:19.487
but that's a sidenote.

00:14:19.487 --> 00:14:21.820
But yeah, everybody has their
things that are just like,

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:23.890
oh my gosh, not that.

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:26.020
But you learn that
there is so much more

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:28.350
good than there is ever bad.

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:31.280
There's a ton of really
positive comments,

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:33.570
and then there's one
that may be really nasty.

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:36.160
But why is it that we
let the bad stick out

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:38.730
so much more than the good?

00:14:38.730 --> 00:14:41.690
And so it's just
trying to refocus.

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:44.494
Because there's always
different places of your mind

00:14:44.494 --> 00:14:46.160
where you can go, but
there's one stage.

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:48.300
And things come in and out,
thoughts come in and out

00:14:48.300 --> 00:14:49.490
all the time, and it's
what thoughts are you

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:50.220
going to entertain?

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:51.010
What thoughts are
you going to let

00:14:51.010 --> 00:14:53.150
stay on the stage of your
mind, and which ones are you

00:14:53.150 --> 00:14:54.399
going to kick off really fast?

00:14:54.399 --> 00:14:56.950
And so I've learned
to just you take it

00:14:56.950 --> 00:14:58.990
all with a grain of
salt. You move on,

00:14:58.990 --> 00:15:00.720
and try to focus on the good.

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:03.497
And especially as you get
bigger and bigger as a YouTuber,

00:15:03.497 --> 00:15:04.830
you get more and more your fans.

00:15:04.830 --> 00:15:06.430
And I have my
little Stirlingites,

00:15:06.430 --> 00:15:08.580
and they will defend
me to the death.

00:15:08.580 --> 00:15:10.780
And if there's a
negative comment,

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:14.859
I usually don't see it, because
they defend me so hardcore.

00:15:14.859 --> 00:15:16.900
How dare you say that
Lindsey's hair looks messy.

00:15:16.900 --> 00:15:17.714
Whatever it is.

00:15:17.714 --> 00:15:20.380
JOHN MERRIFIELD: So I would like
to invite you sister Brooke up.

