and everything, super excited.

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:33.625
And I was at BYU.

00:19:33.625 --> 00:19:35.791
And all these people were
whispering in front of me,

00:19:35.791 --> 00:19:37.560
and then someone tugged
on my little cap,

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:39.101
and they were like,
why are you here?

00:19:42.250 --> 00:19:43.670
I'm graduating.

00:19:43.670 --> 00:19:45.020
I'm not wearing this for style.

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:45.595
JOHN MERRIFIELD:
You're just going

00:19:45.595 --> 00:19:46.705
to bust out and
start playing violin.

00:19:46.705 --> 00:19:47.342
BROOKE PASSEY: They
thought you were doing

00:19:47.342 --> 00:19:48.365
a music video or something.

00:19:48.365 --> 00:19:49.906
LINDSEY STIRLING:
Yeah, they're like,

00:19:49.906 --> 00:19:51.861
is it an impromptu music video?

00:19:51.861 --> 00:19:52.360
Yes.

00:19:52.360 --> 00:19:53.810
Yes, I wanted the cap and gown.

00:19:53.810 --> 00:19:55.030
JOHN MERRIFIELD: So why was
that important for you, though?

00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:57.404
I mean, obviously you are well
established in your career

00:19:57.404 --> 00:19:59.216
and doing well, but
why still graduate?

00:19:59.216 --> 00:20:01.090
LINDSEY STIRLING: You
know, I worked so hard.

00:20:01.090 --> 00:20:02.620
I put myself through college.

00:20:02.620 --> 00:20:05.590
I worked really hard to work
a day job, go to school,

00:20:05.590 --> 00:20:06.840
and pursue music.

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:09.180
And it was something
my entire life,

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:11.130
I always knew I would graduate.

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:13.180
I always knew I
would have a degree.

00:20:13.180 --> 00:20:15.080
And also, it was
something I believed in.

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:19.260
I really did want to become
a recreational therapist.

00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:22.722
And so I couldn't live with
the fact that I was so close

00:20:22.722 --> 00:20:24.680
and I had something that
was so important to me

00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:25.597
that I never finished.

00:20:25.597 --> 00:20:27.346
And so I was like, I
will get that degree.

00:20:27.346 --> 00:20:29.085
And everyone told
me also-- I always

00:20:29.085 --> 00:20:30.919
get inspired and
motivated when people

00:20:30.919 --> 00:20:31.960
say I won't do something.

00:20:31.960 --> 00:20:34.216
And everyone's like, oh
you'll never come back.

00:20:34.216 --> 00:20:35.382
And I was like, yes, I will.

00:20:35.382 --> 00:20:35.882
Yes, I will.

00:20:35.882 --> 00:20:36.792
I'll get that degree.

00:20:36.792 --> 00:20:39.042
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Yeah, we
saw that with "America's Got

00:20:39.042 --> 00:20:39.667
Talent," right?

00:20:39.667 --> 00:20:41.110
LINDSEY STIRLING: That's right.

00:20:41.110 --> 00:20:44.320
I will come back,
and you'll invite me.

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:45.570
BROOKE PASSEY: You'll like it.

00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:46.680
LINDSEY STIRLING:
And you will love it.

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:47.490
JOHN MERRIFIELD: That's awesome.

00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:49.300
So we have a question
from the crowd.

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:51.008
AUDIENCE: So I wanted
to ask a little bit

00:20:51.008 --> 00:20:54.370
about the transition from
classical to not classical

00:20:54.370 --> 00:20:55.984
and how that happened.

00:20:55.984 --> 00:20:57.900
So I was classically
trained as a piano player

00:20:57.900 --> 00:20:59.771
and then became a
computer programmer,

00:20:59.771 --> 00:21:02.145
which is a little bit different
as well, but actually not

00:21:02.145 --> 00:21:02.730
too uncommon.

00:21:02.730 --> 00:21:04.740
I think a lot of
us here do that.

00:21:04.740 --> 00:21:07.740
But I want to hear about
classic violin to your style.

00:21:07.740 --> 00:21:09.930
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yes, so
I'm very grateful that I

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:11.140
was classically trained.

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:13.910
Because those chops as
a classical musician,

00:21:13.910 --> 00:21:15.780
that's important stuff.

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:17.890
That's the foundation
of my playing.

00:21:17.890 --> 00:21:19.800
But I just got really burnt out.

00:21:19.800 --> 00:21:22.050
And I remember, it was right
before I went to college,

00:21:22.050 --> 00:21:24.310
and I was trying to decide
whether I wanted to study music

00:21:24.310 --> 00:21:24.730
or not.

00:21:24.730 --> 00:21:26.438
Like I said, I was
trying to keep it fun,

00:21:26.438 --> 00:21:28.540
but I was like, I don't
enjoy this anymore.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:30.410
I don't love it, and
I used to love it.

00:21:30.410 --> 00:21:31.930
And it made me really sad.

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:33.842
And so it just
clicked in my head.

00:21:33.842 --> 00:21:36.300
Well, I need to play the kind
of music I like to listen to.

00:21:36.300 --> 00:21:38.440
And so I started jamming
with stuff on the radio,

00:21:38.440 --> 00:21:42.080
and I started to play with
bands and write my own music.

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:44.610
And I just really started
to take music into my hands,

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:46.470
rather than just
molding into what

00:21:46.470 --> 00:21:48.540
the violin was supposed to be.

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:50.590
And my passion just
got reinvigorated.

00:21:50.590 --> 00:21:53.990
It became more and more fun,
and I started moving to music.

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:56.230
It looked really
awkward at first.

00:21:56.230 --> 00:22:00.580
And then it just evolved from
there, where I found my sound.

00:22:00.580 --> 00:22:01.717
And that's when I started.

00:22:01.717 --> 00:22:03.300
I was like, I'm going
to make an album

00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:04.760
with this weird, random sound.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:07.880
And it turned out, I
guess, really great.

00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:08.910
It worked.

00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:10.890
JOHN MERRIFIELD: And
you said had literally

00:22:10.890 --> 00:22:13.364
practiced dancing and playing in
front of your roommates, right?

00:22:13.364 --> 00:22:14.155
BROOKE PASSEY: Yes.

00:22:14.155 --> 00:22:16.030
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yes.

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:16.872
I can't believe--

00:22:16.872 --> 00:22:19.330
BROOKE PASSEY: She actually
used their bedroom to practice,

00:22:19.330 --> 00:22:20.880
because ours was too messy.

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:21.433
LINDSEY STIRLING:
Oh, I didn't know

00:22:21.433 --> 00:22:22.960
you were going to say that.

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:25.168
JOHN MERRIFIELD: I don't
know if that's in the books,

00:22:25.168 --> 00:22:26.630
so it's a good tidbit.

00:22:26.630 --> 00:22:29.020
LINDSEY STIRLING: Good
times, good times.

00:22:29.020 --> 00:22:29.690
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:22:29.690 --> 00:22:31.330
Thank you so much
for coming today.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:32.630
So I have a question.

00:22:32.630 --> 00:22:35.790
So you mentioned that
your faith really helped

00:22:35.790 --> 00:22:37.310
when you were sick at the time.

00:22:37.310 --> 00:22:40.902
So would you please elaborate
more, and in what specific way?

00:22:40.902 --> 00:22:41.860
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah.

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:42.850
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:22:42.850 --> 00:22:45.490
LINDSEY STIRLING: I had been
brought up my whole life

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:48.600
to believe that I was a daughter
of God, and that he created me,

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:50.450
and he loved me.

00:22:50.450 --> 00:22:53.900
And anything that you create
we think is beautiful.

00:22:53.900 --> 00:22:55.937
If you have a child, you
think it's beautiful.

00:22:55.937 --> 00:22:57.020
I'm a new mother of a dog.

00:22:57.020 --> 00:22:59.060
I think she's beautiful.

00:22:59.060 --> 00:23:02.430
But anyways, anything that
you are a parent of, you love.

00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:05.380
And so I really had to
delve back into that.

00:23:05.380 --> 00:23:08.450
At this time when I felt
unlovable, and I felt ugly,

00:23:08.450 --> 00:23:10.410
and I just thought
I was worthless,

00:23:10.410 --> 00:23:13.070
I had to remember that
I'm a child of God,

00:23:13.070 --> 00:23:15.060
and I had to rely on
that, that he loves me,

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:18.970
he thinks I'm beautiful,
and I need to love myself,

00:23:18.970 --> 00:23:20.350
so that I can go out.

00:23:20.350 --> 00:23:22.120
Because you can't
love anyone else.

00:23:22.120 --> 00:23:24.130
You can't give any
energy to someone else

00:23:24.130 --> 00:23:26.409
unless you first are
OK with who you are.

00:23:26.409 --> 00:23:27.950
And so I had to heal
myself so that I

00:23:27.950 --> 00:23:29.870
could go out and be
the kind of person

00:23:29.870 --> 00:23:32.510
that God wanted me to be.

00:23:32.510 --> 00:23:33.370
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:23:33.370 --> 00:23:34.470
I'm Ian.

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:36.530
I just wanted to
say I'm a huge fan,

00:23:36.530 --> 00:23:38.730
and I'm actually
a figure skater.

00:23:38.730 --> 00:23:41.010
And I don't know if
you know, but there's

00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:43.590
a huge following for you in
the figuring skating community,

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:45.131
where a lot of
skaters are using some

00:23:45.131 --> 00:23:49.120
of your music for their
numbers, primarily

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:51.250
"Crystallize" and "Element."

00:23:51.250 --> 00:23:54.160
I'm working on trying to do
something with "Anti Gravity."

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:55.368
LINDSEY STIRLING: Oh, really?

00:23:55.368 --> 00:23:56.851
That's cool.

00:23:56.851 --> 00:23:58.850
AUDIENCE: But one of
things I wanted to ask you,

00:23:58.850 --> 00:24:02.070
you mentioned something earlier
about the music industry.

00:24:02.070 --> 00:24:06.520
And I'm curious, when you
started creating your album,

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:10.604
was there any pressure
in terms of the direction

00:24:10.604 --> 00:24:12.520
that some of the songs
had to be created with?

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:14.311
Was there a compromise
that had to be done,

00:24:14.311 --> 00:24:16.870
or just everything was
organic, and it was like,

00:24:16.870 --> 00:24:20.100
this is what I want, and
nobody tell you what to do?

00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:21.950
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah.

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:25.620
Well, it was at the time
my biggest disappointment.

00:24:25.620 --> 00:24:28.151
I could not get a record
label, and I didn't understand

00:24:28.151 --> 00:24:29.400
much about the music industry.

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:31.072
But in my mind,
how it worked was,

00:24:31.072 --> 00:24:32.696
you had to get a
record label if anyone

00:24:32.696 --> 00:24:34.040
was going to hear your tunes.

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:36.890
And then luckily, right
while this was going on,

00:24:36.890 --> 00:24:39.620
I discovered the
wonderful land of YouTube,

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:41.510
and realized, oh my gosh.

00:24:41.510 --> 00:24:43.702
Because I kept hearing,
you're just too different.

00:24:43.702 --> 00:24:46.035
People wanted to put me in a
box of what was successful,

00:24:46.035 --> 00:24:47.365
and they're like,
you're way out there.

00:24:47.365 --> 00:24:49.060
And this is what
we know will work,

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:50.790
and you're way over there.

00:24:50.790 --> 00:24:53.134
And so people were trying
to get me to compromise

00:24:53.134 --> 00:24:55.300
my music in the weirdest
ways, ways that I was like,

00:24:55.300 --> 00:24:57.090
that would never work for me.

00:24:57.090 --> 00:24:58.650
That's not who I am.

00:24:58.650 --> 00:25:00.830
And so I just kept waiting.

00:25:00.830 --> 00:25:02.870
I just kept writing,
waiting, hopefully,

00:25:02.870 --> 00:25:05.610
for someone to love
what I was writing.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:07.630
And then, like I said,
I discovered YouTube.

00:25:07.630 --> 00:25:09.570
And I was so excited
because I realized

00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:12.350
very quickly that here
is a land where I can

00:25:12.350 --> 00:25:14.889
make my music in my own way.

00:25:14.889 --> 00:25:16.180
I could do it on my own timing.

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:17.804
I can do it the way
I want, and there's

00:25:17.804 --> 00:25:18.971
people that want to hear it.

00:25:18.971 --> 00:25:20.762
I don't have to wait
for someone to tell me

00:25:20.762 --> 00:25:23.150
I'm good enough, because all
these people are clicking

00:25:23.150 --> 00:25:24.760
on the links, and
they're liking it,

00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:27.092
and I can see the
iTunes sales spiking

00:25:27.092 --> 00:25:28.300
every time I release a video.

00:25:28.300 --> 00:25:32.190
And so, no, it was all just
the music I wanted to create,

00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:35.851
and my fans told
me they liked it.

00:25:35.851 --> 00:25:38.100
And that's the cool thing
you realize on the internet.

00:25:38.100 --> 00:25:39.440
There's a niche for everything.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:43.609
And so what you create,
create it and they will come.

00:25:43.609 --> 00:25:44.900
JOHN MERRIFIELD: What are they?

00:25:44.900 --> 00:25:46.000
The Stirlingites,
is that what it is?

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:46.960
LINDSEY STIRLING:
Yes, the Stirlingites.

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:48.560
JOHN MERRIFIELD:
Stirlingites, all right.

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:50.101
LINDSEY STIRLING:
I didn't make them.

00:25:50.101 --> 00:25:51.407
They made themselves that.

00:25:51.407 --> 00:25:53.240
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Another
question back here.

00:25:53.240 --> 00:25:54.840
AUDIENCE: So there's also
the unfortunate niche

00:25:54.840 --> 00:25:56.654
of people who want to
say terrible things

00:25:56.654 --> 00:25:57.320
on the internet.

00:25:57.320 --> 00:25:59.060
And you mentioned
this a little bit,

00:25:59.060 --> 00:26:02.430
but I'm curious, being on the
receiving end, not a lot of us

00:26:02.430 --> 00:26:04.910
are on the receiving end as
much as you are, probably,

00:26:04.910 --> 00:26:07.290
of all kinds of comments.

00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:09.540
First of all, why do
you think they do that?

00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:12.030
But secondly and
more importantly,

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:16.555
what can we do as just
humans to help the problem?

00:26:16.555 --> 00:26:18.430
What can we do as Google
to help the problem?

00:26:18.430 --> 00:26:20.860
In your opinion, what
can be done about this?

00:26:20.860 --> 00:26:22.820
Because it's pretty
terrible, and sometimes

00:26:22.820 --> 00:26:26.840
it makes me ashamed
to be a human.

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:29.490
LINDSEY STIRLING: I
know what you mean.

00:26:29.490 --> 00:26:34.090
With this new age of an
extreme amount of technology,

00:26:34.090 --> 00:26:37.940
I just think human
interactions have

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:40.797
become less important
and less precious.

00:26:40.797 --> 00:26:42.380
And people feel like
just because they

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:44.750
don't have a face
to that comment,

00:26:44.750 --> 00:26:47.275
just because they have a
picture of a Pokemon character

00:26:47.275 --> 00:26:50.480
as their icon and their
name is like Skittle27,

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:52.130
it's OK to say
really mean things,

00:26:52.130 --> 00:26:55.040
because there's no
accountability for it.

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:57.260
And so that's why
I think people are.

00:26:57.260 --> 00:27:00.240
And also, I've just realized
people want to be heard.

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:02.240
Everyone wants to feel
like they have a voice.

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:03.830
People are craving
connection, and I

00:27:03.830 --> 00:27:06.090
think the more this
digital age takes off,

00:27:06.090 --> 00:27:08.799
people crave it more
and more, wanting

00:27:08.799 --> 00:27:10.590
to have an identity,
wanting to be noticed,

00:27:10.590 --> 00:27:11.090
wanting to be heard.

00:27:11.090 --> 00:27:12.798
And so I think that's
why a lot of people

00:27:12.798 --> 00:27:14.460
will say really nasty things.

00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:17.534
And then when people like my
little Stirlingites to defend,

00:27:17.534 --> 00:27:18.450
that's what they want.

00:27:18.450 --> 00:27:21.620
They want to fight and
get that interaction.

00:27:21.620 --> 00:27:24.000
But I've just thought a
lot about this lately.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:27.950
Even in stores, like when I'm
checking out at Walgreens,

00:27:27.950 --> 00:27:29.600
how often am I on
my phone and not

00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:31.760
even like looking at the
person that's helping me?

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:34.360
And they ask, do you
want to donate $1?

00:27:34.360 --> 00:27:36.170
I'm like, sure.

00:27:36.170 --> 00:27:39.000
You don't even look up at
people anymore half the time.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.140
And so I've tried to
make a conscious effort

00:27:42.140 --> 00:27:44.020
in my interactions,
whether it's online,

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:46.090
to be personal with
people, or whether it's

00:27:46.090 --> 00:27:48.340
in person, to actually look
people in the eye and say,

00:27:48.340 --> 00:27:51.570
how was your day?

00:27:51.570 --> 00:27:53.160
I think we're all
craving connection,

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:57.172
and people reach out in
weird ways sometimes for it.

00:27:57.172 --> 00:27:58.880
AUDIENCE: If you could
do a collaboration

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:01.500
with any other artist, past
or present, alive or dead,

00:28:01.500 --> 00:28:02.970
who would you pick and why?

00:28:02.970 --> 00:28:04.580
LINDSEY STIRLING: Alive or dead?

00:28:04.580 --> 00:28:06.930
That's so hard.

00:28:06.930 --> 00:28:09.150
OK, I've got two that are dead.

00:28:09.150 --> 00:28:10.340
One of them is a no-brainer.

00:28:10.340 --> 00:28:11.970
Michael Jackson, oh my gosh.

00:28:11.970 --> 00:28:13.820
I would have him give
me a dance tutorial,

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:16.470
and we would do a
remake of "Beat it."

00:28:16.470 --> 00:28:17.869
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Oh wow.

00:28:17.869 --> 00:28:19.910
LINDSEY STIRLING: And
then, also, my other one, I

00:28:19.910 --> 00:28:23.980
would love to do a comedy
sketch with Lucille Ball.

00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:25.230
I love Lucille Ball.

00:28:25.230 --> 00:28:27.340
She's my hero.

00:28:27.340 --> 00:28:29.007
What about you, Brooke?

00:28:29.007 --> 00:28:30.090
BROOKE PASSEY: I'm nobody.

00:28:30.090 --> 00:28:31.839
I don't like being in
front of the camera.

00:28:36.990 --> 00:28:39.349
LINDSEY STIRLING: We're the
same, but really different.

00:28:39.349 --> 00:28:40.099
It's really funny.

00:28:40.099 --> 00:28:41.548
OK.

00:28:41.548 --> 00:28:42.992
JOHN MERRIFIELD: That's awesome.

00:28:42.992 --> 00:28:43.700
Another question?

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:45.158
AUDIENCE: This
question is actually

00:28:45.158 --> 00:28:47.610
coming more from my mother,
who has actually been a violin

00:28:47.610 --> 00:28:49.410
teacher for 40 years now.

00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:53.490
And she has very much fallen
in love with your music,

00:28:53.490 --> 00:28:56.720
and also her students
have as well.

00:28:56.720 --> 00:28:59.230
And so she wants to thank
you for that, first of all,

00:28:59.230 --> 00:29:02.230
for motivating a lot
of very young people

00:29:02.230 --> 00:29:05.050
to basically increase
their motivation

00:29:05.050 --> 00:29:08.140
to learn how to play the
violin, and to actually

00:29:08.140 --> 00:29:11.400
continue to want to do that.

00:29:11.400 --> 00:29:14.280
And it's really fun
to watch her play that

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:16.170
along with your students
like at old folks

00:29:16.170 --> 00:29:19.310
homes and different places,
watch the old folks get up

00:29:19.310 --> 00:29:21.690
and start dancing
and things like that.

00:29:21.690 --> 00:29:24.270
But the question
that she has is she's

00:29:24.270 --> 00:29:26.810
been taking a lot of your
arrangements and your pieces

00:29:26.810 --> 00:29:29.970
and trying to simplify them
a little bit so that younger

00:29:29.970 --> 00:29:31.270
people can play them.

00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:33.462
And so the question
is, is that something

00:29:33.462 --> 00:29:34.670
that you've considered doing?

00:29:34.670 --> 00:29:37.640
Have you consider making--
because a lot of your pieces

00:29:37.640 --> 00:29:42.150
are very difficult. So
that's the question,

00:29:42.150 --> 00:29:45.520
is have you ever considered
creating even simpler versions

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:46.697
of the music that you have?

00:29:46.697 --> 00:29:49.030
LINDSEY STIRLING: You know,
that's such a good-- I have.

00:29:49.030 --> 00:29:53.445
I want to make a violin tutorial
method, like a series of books.

00:29:53.445 --> 00:29:55.360
There's pretty
much one out there.

00:29:55.360 --> 00:29:57.660
It's pretty much one
method that everybody uses.

00:29:57.660 --> 00:29:59.740
And so I wanted to
replace it, but to be

00:29:59.740 --> 00:30:04.370
a supplement to that method
and intersperse my songs along

00:30:04.370 --> 00:30:06.810
with classical violin songs.

00:30:06.810 --> 00:30:08.240
And yeah, simplify some of them.

00:30:08.240 --> 00:30:11.400
I have not done it yet, but
it's definitely something

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:13.110
that I really wanted to do.

00:30:13.110 --> 00:30:16.380
So it's on my list.

00:30:16.380 --> 00:30:19.200
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering
what's the good and bad

00:30:19.200 --> 00:30:21.910
of moving from what you
were doing to getting

00:30:21.910 --> 00:30:24.250
professional management?

00:30:24.250 --> 00:30:30.510
LINDSEY STIRLING: Oh,
well, it's been very great.

00:30:30.510 --> 00:30:33.600
So when I started, I was doing
literally everything myself,

00:30:33.600 --> 00:30:37.979
from thinking of the video
ideas and the creative side

00:30:37.979 --> 00:30:39.520
that I still do and
still love to do,

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:42.830
but also, anytime someone
ordered a piece of merchandise,

00:30:42.830 --> 00:30:44.530
I was the one that
rolled up the poster,

00:30:44.530 --> 00:30:45.990
stuck it in an envelope,
wrote a thank you note,

00:30:45.990 --> 00:30:48.406
and stuck in there, went to
the post office and mailed it.

00:30:48.406 --> 00:30:53.060
I did everything, and
it was overwhelming.

00:30:53.060 --> 00:30:54.234
I couldn't I couldn't focus.

00:30:54.234 --> 00:30:56.150
I stopped being able to
focus on the creative,

00:30:56.150 --> 00:30:58.940
and I was starting to
just run dry of ideas

00:30:58.940 --> 00:31:00.810
because I was so overwhelmed.

00:31:00.810 --> 00:31:03.437
And so getting with
a management company,

00:31:03.437 --> 00:31:05.020
it was actually a
really cool process,

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:06.853
because when I was
searching for management,

00:31:06.853 --> 00:31:10.230
I was very much like,
don't try to change me.

00:31:10.230 --> 00:31:11.420
I'm the way am.

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:12.730
I like to be very hands-on.

00:31:12.730 --> 00:31:15.320
And also, YouTube is the base.

00:31:15.320 --> 00:31:16.560
I don't want a record label.

00:31:16.560 --> 00:31:18.350
And so I was
looking for somebody

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:21.230
that could take who I
was, and then just add

00:31:21.230 --> 00:31:23.862
their knowledge of the
actual real music industry

00:31:23.862 --> 00:31:24.570
and how it works.

00:31:24.570 --> 00:31:26.380
And so it's this
amazing thing where

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:27.820
we've learned from each other.

00:31:27.820 --> 00:31:29.421
I found the right
management company.

00:31:29.421 --> 00:31:31.170
My manager's right
back there in the back.

00:31:31.170 --> 00:31:32.350
Adina, give a wave.

00:31:32.350 --> 00:31:34.365
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:36.340 --> 00:31:38.100
I would say that the
hard thing about it

00:31:38.100 --> 00:31:39.755
is just finding
the right manager.

00:31:39.755 --> 00:31:40.990
It was really hard.

00:31:40.990 --> 00:31:43.320
I was managerless
for quite a while

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:45.220
because I was searching
for the right fit.

00:31:45.220 --> 00:31:46.590
It's like dating, you know?

00:31:46.590 --> 00:31:48.217
It's like looking
for-- because I

00:31:48.217 --> 00:31:50.550
felt like I was going on all
these dates with management

00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:51.510
companies and meetings.

00:31:51.510 --> 00:31:53.595
And then finally, when
you find the right people,

00:31:53.595 --> 00:31:54.970
it clicks, and
it's been amazing.

00:31:54.970 --> 00:31:58.510
But yeah, that process
was exhausting.

00:31:58.510 --> 00:32:01.060
AUDIENCE: I know you've worked
with an old friend of mine,

00:32:01.060 --> 00:32:02.660
Devin Graham.

00:32:02.660 --> 00:32:04.510
I went to high school with him.

00:32:04.510 --> 00:32:05.832
We shot a video together.

00:32:05.832 --> 00:32:06.790
LINDSEY STIRLING: Nice.

00:32:06.790 --> 00:32:08.730
AUDIENCE: And I know
you've worked with him.

00:32:08.730 --> 00:32:11.860
I think you still do, your
latest Final Fantasy video,

00:32:11.860 --> 00:32:13.600
I think.

00:32:13.600 --> 00:32:17.350
And you also had a relationship
with him for a good while.

00:32:17.350 --> 00:32:18.630
How has--

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:20.386
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Sorry.

00:32:20.386 --> 00:32:20.879
Just throwing that one in there.

00:32:20.879 --> 00:32:21.865
LINDSEY STIRLING: Am I blushing?

00:32:21.865 --> 00:32:22.365
Yes.

00:32:22.365 --> 00:32:25.450
JOHN MERRIFIELD: You dated him,
in case you didn't know that.

00:32:25.450 --> 00:32:26.622
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I know.

00:32:26.622 --> 00:32:29.700
It's not there anymore,
but you're still working.

00:32:29.700 --> 00:32:32.230
You're still working
with him after the fact.

00:32:32.230 --> 00:32:35.880
And I just wanted to know
how, having worked with him,

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:40.110
how easygoing, or was
it difficult to work

00:32:40.110 --> 00:32:43.040
with other celebrities?

00:32:43.040 --> 00:32:43.707
Like YouTubers?

00:32:43.707 --> 00:32:46.040
You were saying you have many
friends who are YouTubers.

00:32:46.040 --> 00:32:50.240
How does working and having
a relationship with one

00:32:50.240 --> 00:32:53.350
affect your career?

00:32:53.350 --> 00:32:55.882
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah,
I actually met Devin.

00:32:55.882 --> 00:32:58.090
He's the one that introduced
me to the YouTube world.

00:32:58.090 --> 00:32:59.100
He contacted me.

00:32:59.100 --> 00:33:01.480
I saw this little video I had.

00:33:01.480 --> 00:33:04.500
And it was my "America's
Got Talent" video he saw.

00:33:04.500 --> 00:33:06.130
And he reached out
to me, and was like,

00:33:06.130 --> 00:33:07.972
I think you would do
really well on YouTube.

00:33:07.972 --> 00:33:09.680
And I was just like,
I didn't understand.

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:10.513
I was like, YouTube?

00:33:10.513 --> 00:33:11.690
I don't get it.

00:33:11.690 --> 00:33:13.530
And so he actually taught this.

00:33:13.530 --> 00:33:17.839
He used to teach classes
on here's YouTube.

00:33:17.839 --> 00:33:19.380
Be introduced to
the land of YouTube.

00:33:19.380 --> 00:33:20.846
This is how you be a YouTuber.

00:33:20.846 --> 00:33:22.220
And I went to one
of his classes.

00:33:22.220 --> 00:33:24.110
He invited me, and
I was like, wow.

00:33:24.110 --> 00:33:24.640
What?

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:26.460
And my life was
changed in that moment.

00:33:26.460 --> 00:33:27.840
And I was like, this is
what I'm going to do.

00:33:27.840 --> 00:33:30.089
And so I owe so much to Devin
Graham, because not only

00:33:30.089 --> 00:33:32.100
that, we started
working together a ton,

00:33:32.100 --> 00:33:35.270
we started dating.

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:37.000
But it was amazing.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.050
The two of us were chasing
our dreams together,

00:33:39.050 --> 00:33:41.100
and we are getting to
travel the world together,

00:33:41.100 --> 00:33:43.032
and both doing what we loved.

00:33:43.032 --> 00:33:45.240
And we would help each other
with our projects, which

00:33:45.240 --> 00:33:48.480
was amazing, and really hard
to end a relationship, though,

00:33:48.480 --> 00:33:50.224
that's based on everything.

00:33:50.224 --> 00:33:51.640
We were each other's
best friends.

00:33:51.640 --> 00:33:52.270
We were dating.

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:54.980
We were also each other's
coworkers, pretty much.

00:33:54.980 --> 00:33:56.250
We did everything together.

00:33:56.250 --> 00:33:57.750
And so I remember
thinking my career

00:33:57.750 --> 00:33:59.490
was over when we ended it.

00:33:59.490 --> 00:34:03.030
I was like, OK, that was the
worst decision I ever made.

00:34:03.030 --> 00:34:04.780
I didn't know how I
was going to continue,

00:34:04.780 --> 00:34:06.400
because he was my
cinematographer.

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:07.820
He was my partner-in-crime.

00:34:07.820 --> 00:34:10.880
And so it was really interesting
to renavigate the waters.

00:34:10.880 --> 00:34:13.429
How do I do this
without the guy that

00:34:13.429 --> 00:34:15.790
taught me everything I
know, and has helped me

00:34:15.790 --> 00:34:17.420
every step of the way so far?

00:34:17.420 --> 00:34:19.260
But like I said,
I owe everything

00:34:19.260 --> 00:34:22.496
pretty much that I have to
what Devin Graham did for me,

00:34:22.496 --> 00:34:23.620
and he's an amazing person.

00:34:23.620 --> 00:34:25.699
So here's to Devinsupertramp.

00:34:25.699 --> 00:34:27.085
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:28.010 --> 00:34:30.645
JOHN MERRIFIELD: So what's
next for Lindsey Stirling?

00:34:30.645 --> 00:34:31.900
LINDSEY STIRLING: What's next?

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:35.159
You know, this book is what's
been next for so long, so it's

00:34:35.159 --> 00:34:36.239
crazy that now it's out.

00:34:36.239 --> 00:34:38.989
And now I'm working
on an album, and I'm

00:34:38.989 --> 00:34:39.989
really excited about it.

00:34:39.989 --> 00:34:41.655
I'm about halfway
done with it, and it's

00:34:41.655 --> 00:34:44.295
going to come out in
June, fingers crossed.

00:34:44.295 --> 00:34:47.219
It's my self-proclaimed
deadline.

00:34:47.219 --> 00:34:49.120
But yeah, and I'm super
stoked about that.

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:51.659
We'll be touring and doing
festivals through the summer

00:34:51.659 --> 00:34:52.659
and touring in the fall.

00:34:52.659 --> 00:34:54.723
So that's pretty much
what's next for me.

00:34:54.723 --> 00:34:55.639
JOHN MERRIFIELD: Cool.

00:34:55.639 --> 00:34:57.353
Well, thank you so much
for your time, Lindsey.

00:34:57.353 --> 00:34:58.319
This was really good.

00:34:58.319 --> 00:35:00.402
LINDSEY STIRLING: Yeah,
thank you guys for coming.

